Introduction¶

In this project we will be analysing The Movie Database (TMDb) which contains information of over 10,000 movies including budget, revenue, cast, title, release year etc. And we'll be focus on the parameters that contributes towards the success of a movie.

Questions that can be analysed from this data set:¶

  1. What are top 10 most and least profitable movies?
  2. What are top 10 most and least expensive movies of all time?
  3. What are top 10 most and least popular movies of all time?
  4. What is average runtime distribution of the movies?
  5. On which year the movies released was the highest?
  6. Is the average runtime of movies consistent throughout the years?
  7. How is popularity related to profit?
  8. How is budget related to profit?
  9. Which month has most movie releases?
  10. What is the correlation between each parameters?
  11. What are the most frequent genres, actor and director?
  12. Which is the most profitable genre, actor and director?
  13. What are most profitable production companies?
  14. What are some parameters that are related to movies with high revenue?

Question 1. What are top 10 most and least profitable movies?¶

Firstly, lets checkout the top 10 most profitable movies.

In [409]:
# sorting the data in descending order according to profit and plotting a bar graph showing top 10 movies
most_profit=df.sort_values(['profit'],ascending=False)[:10][['original_title','profit']]
most_profit.set_index('original_title',inplace=True)
most_profit.plot(kind ='bar',figsize=(8,5))

#setup the labels of the plot
plt.title('Top 10 movies with the most profit',fontsize=15);
plt.ylabel('Profit in billions ($)',fontsize=12);
plt.xlabel('Movie Title',fontsize=12);
sns.set_style('darkgrid')

Now lets find out the least 10 profitable movies.

In [410]:
# sorting the data in ascending order according to profit and plotting a bar graph showing top 10 movies
least_profit=df.sort_values(['profit'],ascending=True)[:10][['original_title','profit']]
least_profit.set_index('original_title',inplace=True)
least_profit.plot(kind ='bar',figsize=(8,5),color='orange')

#setup the labels of the plot
plt.title('Top 10 movies with the least profit',fontsize=15);
plt.ylabel('Profit in billions ($)',fontsize=12);
plt.xlabel('Movie Title',fontsize=12);
sns.set_style('darkgrid')

It is observed that Avatar is the most profitable movie and The Warrior's Way is the least profitable movie.¶

Question 5. On which year the movies released was the highest?¶

In [416]:
# grouping the data by release year and counting the movies released in each year
year_release=df.groupby('release_year').count()['original_title']

# plotting the result using a line plot
year_release.plot(kind = 'line',xticks = np.arange(1960,2016,5),figsize = (10,5), color = 'purple')

#setup the labels of the plot
plt.xlabel('Release Year', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('No. of movies', fontsize=12)
plt.title('Movies released over the years', fontsize=15);

Question 5. Is release year of the movie associated with the profit?¶

In [419]:
# grouping the data by release year and summing the profit made in each year and plotting the graph b/w profit and release year
df.groupby('release_year')['profit'].sum().plot(kind='line',xticks = np.arange(1960,2016,5), figsize=(10,5), color='purple')

#setup the labels of the plot
plt.xlabel('Release Year', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Total Profit in billions ($)', fontsize=12)
plt.title('Total Profit over the years', fontsize=15);

It is observed that with the increasing time, the total profit made in each year is also increasing.¶

Question 6. Is the average runtime of movies consistent throughout the years?¶

In [436]:
# grouping the data by release year and calculating the mean of runtime of every made that year
avg_runtime=df.groupby('release_year').mean()['runtime']
avg_runtime.plot(kind = 'line',xticks = np.arange(1960,2016,5), figsize = (10,5), color = 'b');

#setup the labels of the plot
plt.title("Runtime over the years",fontsize=15);
plt.xlabel('Year',fontsize=12);
plt.ylabel('Runtime',fontsize=12);

It is observed that back in the days, the length of the movie used to much longer as compared to the latest movies.¶

Question 7. How is popularity related to profit?¶

In [421]:
ax = sns.regplot(x=df['popularity'],y=df['profit'],color='b')

#setup the labels of the plot
ax.set_title("Popularity Vs Profit",fontsize=15)
ax.set_xlabel("Popularity",fontsize=12)
ax.set_ylabel("Profit in billion ($)",fontsize=12)

sns.set(rc={'figure.figsize':(8,5)})
sns.set_style('whitegrid')

It is observed that profit is positively correlated with popularity which means that movie with high popularity tends to make higher profit.¶

Question 12. Which is the most profitable genre, actor and director?¶

In [433]:
#selecting the data which has made higher profit than the total average profit made.
top_profit=df[df['profit']>df['profit'].mean()][['profit','genres','cast','director','production_companies']]

#splitting the genre column to extract the data 
genre_data=top_profit['genres'].str.cat(sep='|')
genres = pd.Series(genre_data.split('|'))

#plotting a pie chart of genre which are most profitable
genres.value_counts(ascending=False).head(17).plot(kind='pie',figsize=(8,8));

As vote count is not consistent for all the movies so it is not a good parameter determining the revenue.

Budget vs Revenue The correlation between revenue and budget is 0.6714. There is a good possibility that movies with higher investments result in better revenues.

Popularity vs Revenue The correlation between revenue and popularity is 0.5915. We can say that if the popularity of movie is high then the revenue of the movie may be high.

Vote Average vs Revenue The correlation between revenue and vote average is 0.2069. So vote average is not highly related to the revenue.

Runtime vs Revenue The correlation between revenue and runtime is 0.2378. So runtime is not highly related to the revenue.

Conclusions¶

From the above analysis, it can be concluded that the following criteria should be fulfilled in order to create a profitable movie.

  1. Genre of the movie must be in : Action, Adventure, Thriller, Comedy, Drama.
  2. Tom Crusie, Brad Pitt, Tom Hanks or Sylvester Stallone should be selected as cast of the movie.
  3. Steven Spielberg, Robert Zemeckis, Clint Eastwood or Tim Burton should be the director of the movie for its better performance.
  4. Universal Pictures, Warner Bros., Paramount Pictures or Twentieth Century Fox Film Corporation should be the production co. of the movie.
  5. The runtime of the movie must be close to 2 hours.

Limitations¶

The above conclusion is not a 100% accurate as it only takes into considerations those movies that have made a considerable amount of profit. Some movies like some indie movies do not have such large investments but they sometimes do well in the market.

Also, the budget and revenue columns did not specify currency so there may be some differences due to fluctuating exchange rates. Different countries may also have different rules and regulations they have to follow which may restrict them from artistiic freedom.

Rows with NaN values were dropped, hence a lot of important data might have been lost in the process.

There are a lot of crew members apart from the director, cast and the production companies who help in creating a movie like writers, screenplay writers, editors, etc. but there was no data to analyse those aspects.
